The best move in the position. White performs the final killing blow. The
knight cannot capture because it's pinned; so, the king is forced to recapture.
By this brilliant exchange rook sacrifice, White opens up the position of the
king. Please also notice that White has a piece superiority on the kingside
and he can bring the pieces there very fast. Black cannot do the same, bring a
lot of defenders.} (19. Bd3 $5) (19. Bc4 $5) 19... Kxh7 20. Qxf6 {White has a
good position because his queen is extremely active, covering squares around
the enemy king. White can bring the rook to h1, and the g6-pawn is weak.} Qg7
21. Ng5+ Kh8 22. Qf4 $1 {This is a very important attacking rule: While you're
attacking, you need to keep the queens on the board. The Be2 isn't important
because White would like to win time for the attack.} Rxe2 23. Rh1+ Kg8 24.
Qc4+ {White will collect back the rook on e2 and he has a winning position.
White won the game smoothly.} d5 25. Qxe2 Qf6 26. Qe3 Rd8 27. Nh7 Qd6 28. Qg5
Kf7 29. Qh4 Rg8 30. Ng5+ Kf8 31. Re1 Bc8 32. Ne6+ 1-0

