1. e4 c5 2. d3 Nc6 3. g3 e6 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. f4 Be7 6. Nf3 O-O 7. O-O b6 8. Nc3
Bb7 9. h3 Ne8 10. f5 Nc7 11. g4 f6 12. Bd2 b5 {Diagram #} 13. Ne2 $5 {
The Closed Sicilian is a very tricky system to meet. White controls the center
solidly and, step by step, he will start building his kingside attack. Black
has the illusion that he can control the d4-square (actually, he controls it),
but on this square he cannot do anything. In most of the cases, Black placed a
knight on d4, but this knight is not coordinated with the remaining pieces; so,
it's not dangerous. Please also notice that already White manages to play f5
and this is very favorable forhim!} (13. Nh4 $5) (13. Bf4 $5) (13. Be3 $5)
13... Ne5 14. Nf4 Nxf3+ 15. Qxf3 {After the exchange of the knights, White
increased his superiority on the kingside, and he is ready to continue
building his attack there. White is controlling well the center, the d3 and
e4-pawns are restricting the bishop on b7.} b4 16. h4 {White has a fantastic
space advantage on the queenside, but his pieces are not supporting the pawns,
and this is a problem. On the other hand, White has a lot of pieces on the
kingside. His pawns are ready to perform the g5 advancement, but White needs
to prepare it with his pieces. In chess, as in life, you need to be patient.
First, White should prepare it and then perform it.} Bd6 17. Qf2 Rb8 18. Be3
Qe7 19. Rae1 Nb5 20. Nh5 {White has the initiative here because his pieces are
on the kingside and they are preparing the attack. The computer assesses this
position as equal, but White has a clear breakthrough, the g5. It's a little
more difficult to suggest good and active plans for Black. White manages to
win the game afterwards.} Nd4 21. Bf4 Bxf4 22. Nxf4 Nc6 23. Re3 Ne5 24. Rg3 Nf7
25. Nh5 h6 26. g5 hxg5 27. hxg5 Nxg5 28. e5 Bxg2 29. Qxg2 exf5 30. exf6 gxf6
31. Nxf6+ Rxf6 32. Rxg5+ Kh7 33. Rh5+ Rh6 34. Rxh6+ Kxh6 35. Qh2+ Kg6 36. Qxb8
1-0

