bxc3 d6 9. e4 e5 10. d5 Ne7 11. Nh4 h6 12. f3 g5 13. Nf5 Nxf5 14. exf5 Bd7 15.
Bd2 Kg7 16. g4 Rh8 17. Rb1 Rb8 18. Kg2 a6 19. a4 b6 {Diagram #} 20. Rh1 $1 {
The exclamation mark isn't for the move itself but for the plan! White is
preparing to open the kingside position with the h4 move. The queen will go to
c2, and then White can double the rooks on the h-file. By this plan, White
creates a stronger army on the kingside. The real problem for Black, the
strategical problem, is that he cannot create any active counterplay or a
stronger army on the other side of the board.} (20. Qc2 $5) (20. h4 $5 {This
is interesting, but it's better to prepare this move with your pieces before
playing it.}) 20... Nh7 21. Qc2 Rb7 22. Be3 {White just continues with his
preparation moves. It's very difficult, or impossible, for Black to play b5...}
Qf6 23. h4 {Everything was ready for the breakthrough, and White finally
performed it.} gxh4 24. Bf2 {The h4-pawn is doomed. Black cannot protect it
sufficiently. And please also note how, step by step, White is creating a
stronger army on the kingside.} Ng5 25. Rxh4 Qd8 26. Rbh1 $16 {White performed
his plan and, as you can understand, he is totally protecting the e4-square.
Black cannot play easily the b5 break, the h6-pawn is weak, the g5 knight
looks OK, but it doesn't coordinate with the remain pieces. So, White is ready
to continue building his attack on the kingside, the side where he has a
stronger army. He manages to win the game afterwards.} f6 27. Be3 b5 28. axb5
axb5 29. Kg3 bxc4 30. Qh2 Nf7 31. Bxh6+ Kg8 32. Be4 Be8 33. Be3 Rxh4 34. Qxh4
